10:28.768 --> 10:40.261
classes in the hallway and the school cafeteria 
and everyone had to stand in line to go to the

10:28.768 --> 10:40.261
restroom. Yet we had some splendid teachers and 
everything seemed orderly. In hindsight, it is

10:49.195 --> 11:11.018
astonishing how crime-free that boomtown was as 
we listened at the news from Europe and the Pacific

10:49.195 --> 11:11.018
in what seemed to us to be some very tough years, 
some very tough months.

11:21.646 --> 11:49.392
After perhaps two years in the trailer house, we 
were able to move to

11:21.646 --> 11:49.392
the Riverside Edition, a newly created 
government housing project

11:21.646 --> 11:49.392
northeast of the older part of Orange, which was 
created out of a swamp.

11:52.274 --> 12:21.825
The

11:52.274 --> 12:21.825
construction of Riverside had come about when 
engineers went in and cut down the cypress trees in

11:52.274 --> 12:21.825
the swamp, quickly pumped sand out of the Sabine 
River, and then put prefab housing on that

11:52.274 --> 12:21.825
location to accommodate perhaps 10,000 
residents.

12:24.387 --> 12:31.734
It was big enough that there were three elementary 
schools just to serve Riverside.

12:31.754 --> 12:44.347
By the fall of 1943, the new high school for Urange 
had opened

12:31.754 --> 12:44.347
just east of what had been the old high school. The 
new high school named in honor of Mr. Stark, Stark

12:46.669 --> 12:53.196
High School. with Tigers as the traditional

12:55.133 --> 13:06.074
mascot name and orange and black the school 
colors. The old high school building became Helen

13:08.619 --> 13:16.635
Carr Junior High in honor of the longtime high 
school principal.

13:19.838 --> 13:29.487
But still, the Bengal Guards and Lancers included 
students from both institutions.

13:29.507 --> 13:44.322
During those years, we had quickly joined the 
First Presbyterian Church there and once more

13:29.507 --> 13:44.322
encountered the generosity of the Stark family.

13:47.545 --> 13:48.026
H.J. Lutcher Stark's mother, had financed the 
construction of the splendid

13:51.293 --> 14:07.576
pink granite building for the First Presbyterian 
Church down at 8th and Green Avenue.

14:11.562 --> 14:20.895
It was built in the first decade of the century at a 
very high cost for that era. and included some

14:21.753 --> 14:30.348
prize winning windows, stained glass windows 
that she had bought at the Chicago World's Fair.

14:34.034 --> 14:47.136
Even at church, some of us played in a little band 
and we learned that Mr. Stark's idea for the Bengal

14:34.034 --> 14:47.136
Guards and Lancers had started with the band that a 
little musical organization that he had helped

14:47.993 --> 14:59.644
underwrite in the mid-1930s.

15:07.931 --> 15:08.792
The Reverend E.T. Drake was the longtime minister 
at the church. Having started his ministry there

15:19.060 --> 15:28.855
as a student, a palestine student at the Austin 
Presbyterian Seminary. It was the only

15:30.718 --> 15:35.785
congregation he ever served and he did so with 
great dignity. Another distinction of that

15:36.987 --> 15:44.258
building is that it was the first air-conditioned 
building west of the Mississippi and perhaps the

15:36.987 --> 15:44.258
first in the world. The Stark family, once more, 
the Stark family had

15:45.436 --> 16:03.164
underwritten the construction of an ice making 
plant in a building just north of the church

15:45.436 --> 16:03.164
sanctuary. Then fans blew air over the blocks of 
ice through a duct system into the church

16:04.205 --> 16:12.338
building.

